text: You can tell it’s the same haters from the first movie, because they keep on regurgitating the same argument: “it looks like Power Rangers.”  That was the exact same argument against the first. No thanks to the past years, we were just conditioned to hate things. We are now conditioned to hate joy, colour, fun. And often the reply below such a comment would be “Um, actually…” Y You hate this, fine, whatever. But don’t try to muscle in on another guys enjoyment of a piece that is ultimately harmless good-natured fun. Giant robots vs giant monsters? No shit it’s going to be dumb. But it’s going to be fun to a large portion of people! Now something that is sexist, racist and out right bigoted, fine. But don’t try to ruin someone’s joy for a franchise just because you want to shove down random people’s throats your opinion and then attack them when they don’t care about and/or except it. And then don’t try to treat the person pointing out this crap that your spewing like a dumbass, by posting reams and reams of text trying to point out how “ UH, actually it is wrong because of this....” I look forward to whatever rando tries to degrade comments like this, while I wait for this giant monster movie I’ve been getting excited about for years for.

text: Ok,so let's break down everything wrong with this trailer.  1. Feeling of weight. Now pardon me if I sound like a billion other people when saying this,but unfortunately it is quite a prevalent issue,HOW IN THE FLYING FUCK ARE THE JAEGERS MOVING AROUND LIKE THAT?! It looks as if they're hollow cardboard cut-outs in terms of weight. I don't care if this is sci-fi,you have to at least TRY to have a hint of realism in there,otherwise you break the suspension of disbelief. And quite frankly,a 7000 ton,250 foot tall robot wouldn't be able to do half this stuff without collapsing under it's own weight. This looks like a freaking video game.  2. The setting. In the first movie you were always in the dark and the rain. The only true daylight scenes are in the beginning and the end of the movie. This is supposed to convey humanity's downward spiral towards the later half of the war,the twilight before the destruction of everything. The beginning is bright to signify humanity uniting and temporarily winning against the threat and the end...well ends with a sunrise to signify the beginning of a new era of peace. In this one it looks like a Michael Bay movie. No drama,no suspense,nothing,just bright sunny days to emphasize...idk. Also,in the first the darkness served a practical purpose as well,disguising some of CGI. Now don't get me wrong,the CGI is amazing,but inevitably there are going to be parts that look crappier that others. But that's the good thing about the darkness,that it hides these below average effects and let's you fully enjoy a scene without breaking the immersion. In this one...I refer back to my video game point.  3. The designs of the Jaegers themselves. These are incredibly generic designs for mechas. Aside from Gipsy Avenger,who's already ripping off two existing designs,namely the OG Gipsy and Striker Eureka,none of them stand out. In the first one,each Jaeger had a unique design which told exactly who they were and what fuction they played. Cherno's the tough bruiser,Crimson's the nimble fighter,Gipsy is the heroic brawler and Striker's the futuristic one. Now,all of them are the Striker Eureka archetype,except this time it's uninspired and old.  And finally,this might be just a problem with the trailer but still: 4.The music. In the first you had booming orchestral themes evoking the epicness of the situation and a sense of grandeur. Here,you have a shitty ass pop song that sounds like a million others meant to just appeal to the kiddies that wanna be "lit" and "cool".  It's pathetic how much of a sellout this feels. Pacific Rim seems to be another franchise that's succumbing to having it's soul sucked by the corporate executives. And I really,really hope I'm wrong about this and it turns out alright,but as it is now...Cthulhu help us.

text: After the first trailer, I was extremely hesitant. Uprising just didn't seem to capture the spirit of the original. The Jaegers and Kaijus didn't look as real, there didn't seem to be as much lovely attention to detail that made them feel so... yeah, so real in the original. But now, I'm more hopeful. They did look pretty solid in some shots, and while little was given away about the story, it looks promising. Despite definitely being a different movie, you can now see more clearly that this is, like the original, a character-driven story. So... I don't know. Maybe this will still be good after all. I hope so. I'd scream if the sequel to my favourite movie of all time sucked! Why did you have to leave, delToro? Why? At least delToro was still a co-writer of the script, so it'll hopefully be good.  That said... please keep the music of the original! Pleasepleaseplease! I know it's a different composer, and of course he can do his own interpretation, but there just has to be at least one scene, preferably a drop scene, with the full, barely changed main theme from Ramin Djawadi!  I'm extremely hyped and extremely terrified at the same time. Please let this movie be good...

text: Man I hope it isn't going to suck but it probably will. Guillermo del Toro made the first one so epic because he realy cared about making this movie and bringing a mecha style movie to the west. This one is from another director and you can clearly see that. The combat and mechs look lighter and faster wich in my opinion is a bad thing. The slow, heavy and mechanical way the mechs moved in the first one added alot to style and tone off the movie. The colours are also just off. This movie looks like it will almost all be in daylight with just bland collours. The previous movie was way darker with small neon lights in between it and heavy rainfall making the mechs all wet and reflect the small lights. None off the amazing collours from the previous movie are present in this one. It looks more like a transformers movie then the next Pacific Rim. Man I hope im all wrong but it doesn't look good.

text: I feel like this movie leans towards its “teenage audience” unlike the first film. You get those vibes just listening to this pop music, and I’d much prefer the dramatic orchestrated music. Also, I don’t complain about the physics behind the robots, but I feel their designs need more differentiation. The first film had robots that played unique roles; The tank, the mobile, the advanced and the underdog. Here, of course those roles are fulfilled but their general designs obviously look very similar. Furthermore, for a movie showing the human race once again on the edge of extinction, why in broad daylight? I’d much prefer seeing this mostly in a dark time scenario since it’d much better suit the theme of the monster apocalypse.

text: I'm gonna be honest. I am a huge Pacific rim fan, I watched the movie so many times, I collected the neca figures. And read the comic. But this trailer looks bad to me, now I really want this movie to be good. Hell, fuck good, I want it to be great, like the first movie. But it looks bad. Here's my opinion (agree of disagree, I would love to hear more peoples opinions) first of all, the actual jeagers. They look like shit, in the first movie, they had personality, you wouldn't confuse one with another. Each one of em looks like they would be built from the country they were from. Also, they moved like actual robots, slow, and heavy. Like Cherno Alpha moves has slow movement, and they give a scale of weight on him just by the way it sounds and moves. While Crimson has slow graceful movements ts, and also has a scale of weight on him. In this one, they all move they their weightless. Second, the story kinda looks cheesy, but the first move was cheesy but let's hope they don't go over bored. 3, in the first movie. The characters had to have things attached to the suit, that would move the jeager, it have weight on the actors and you could tell, they had a hard time moving, it gave the robots a feeling that you needed to know what you were doing to operat one of the jeagers. Now they don't have one. And that kinda sucks. Anyway, that's my opinion if you think differently, or spotted something I said that wasn't true. Feel free to reply with it.

text: A lot of people are complaining that this isn't the same gritty or dark feel as the first movie. A lot of people's issue with the first was that the characters took themselves too seriously. This movie is designed to be an excuse for giant robots and monsters fight. Pacific Rim isn't getting a sequel because it had a great story. author: Walker Michaud

text: Frankly this looks terrible. There were tons of caricature in the original Pacific Rim that made it funny and campy, but it was also gritty and mechanical. The original PacRim jaegers were different in structure in order to counter the large variety of kaiju - the sequel makes all kaiju look the same. Why there is infighting amongst humans when species extinction threatens all is such an awful hook. Worst still is how some teenager managed to come up with a technology that took scientists years to perfect with human casualties involved in it. Dealbreaker for me was the rap music... Why? PacRim had an amazing soundtrack.

text: This movie seems like it's going to be one of those average marvel movies that come out every 2 seconds. yeah, it's not marvel, but you know what I mean. I got some issues and this is only the trailer. Look at the lighting in this trailer. Bright, elaborate, exotic isn't it? Now find any scene from the first movie. Besides the city lights in Tokyo, there is no point where the lighting is every that bright. It's always dim and gave this sense of eerieness almost like it's the end of the god damn world... oh wait. When I look at this, I don't get the same effect it doesn't feel tense, it doesn't feel suspenseful. I really don't want this movie to be average or bad and ruin the franchise. I have no idea why they wanted to do a pacific rim movie without Guillermo del Toro, but they're about to regret it.

text: I've read through the comment section, and agree with a lot of you. I'll add my 2 cents though. What was awesome about the fights in the 1st movie was that you got the emotional impact of the fight, you felt some level of connection with each Yaeger's pilots, and when each one went down swinging, it brought a tear to my eye. The orchestral score was rhythmic and mechanical to match the mechanical nature of the Yaeger's. Now we have big Power Rangers basically. They fly, they transform, they fight in packs, they all have bright colors so you can tell which is which. Add in the teenager lead roles, and it's further proof this was a sequel that no one expected, and few people now want. If you want a great "kids save the day" film, watch Ender's Game!

text: I wasn’t too sure about this after I watched the first time, but after watching again I think they have some pretty cool ideas. In Voltron and Power Rangers the mechs combine into one giant robot to fight the bad guys, but it looks like they turned that on its head and are making the kaiju “morph” together into one bigger enemy. The white mechs that open the breach have 3 fingers, it appears, and look very alien. Are they somehow controlled by the kaiju masters? Who on earth would strike a deal with them, and why? I like that the jaegers are still very different from each other, as in the first film it was stated that the kaiju were “adapting” to human jaeger tactics. The young pilots seem odd at first, but I would have made a way better pilot at 17 than at 30, so maybe it’s not that weird. The kids in Ender’s Game (the book) accomplished feats adults couldn’t because their minds hadn’t been put into boxes yet. I buy that.  Honestly this trailer doesn’t look great, but that’s what I thought when I saw the trailer for the first film, as well. I only gave it a chance because Del Toro’s name was on it. I strapped myself in for a terrible action movie. But after that first fight, where Beckett has to watch his brother get ripped out of the cockpit, then gets his jaeger torn apart, I realized I was actually watching a good movie, and changed my attitude. It was cheesy, silly, full of one-liners, fake action and plot holes, but it was a GOOD MOVIE.  This trailer looks bad, but so did the trailers for the originals. I’m still going to see it and I hope I’ll be as surprised as I was the first time.

text: 1 minor complaint: the first movie does amazing things with the scale of the jaegers. Every single action they take, you can feel the mass behind their body, whether when they're moving through the ocean, walking in the road, or brawling with the kaijiu. In this one, we definitely get that sense of weight when they interact with the environment, but less so when fighting the other jaeger and engaging the kaijiu. I dunno, they just feel a bit too acrobatic for 300 foot robots.

text: Cant wait to see it. It just pisses me off that nyctophiliac are bashing on the film, just because there are no dark tones like the first one.  Look, the dark tones in the first film served its purpose. Hope was nearly gone. It would make no sense to do that again, because that hope is reguvinated. And a prequel wouldve just been a rehash of the first film.  I just dont get what is so wrong about being able to see these damn mechs now? Can anyone *really* say they fully enjoyed the fights in the first film? The ones with all the rain and mist, and majority of the film taking place at night?  I also like the mechs here are faster. I never did understood that, something giant moving slow, instead of moving like a regular person would. The Zord fight in Power Rangers 2017 had that problem too, hopefully that gets fixed in its sequel.  And when it comes to the new characters, one of the old characters from the first film is here too. So, Im sure we'll see Gypsy Danger fight(but I hope they dont kill the two off).

text: So this couple goes on a camping trip. Planned by a Environmental Analyst, he wanted to take his girlfriend who loves Astronomy out to the woods to enjoy the crystal clear view of the stars. The arrived around Noon and set up their tent, campfire and lived for the day until nightfall. As they gazed upon the stars, the couple returned to their tent to fall asleep. The boyfriend woke up in the middle of the night. "Babe. Babe!" He shook his girlfriend awake. "Hmm?". "Look up. What do you see?". She shifted. "I see millions of stars". "And what do you make from that?".  "Well, if there are millions of stars... There must be planets around some of them. And if there are millions of planets... There must be life out there somewhere!". She paused. "No." The boyfriend said. "It means someone stole our tent!".

text: Looks like a bit of fun but doesn't have the same feel the first gave me to be honest. And it kind of feels like it undermines one of the major themes of the first film. While still being a Saturday morning cartoon of a film the first film still had a major theme of human beings uniting for once and being able to beat back a seemingly invincible foe because of it. But I may be overthinking a concept about robots punching monsters.   Also a side note, the mechs don't look like they have any weight to them, at all.   But i guess we'll see how good it is when it comes out.
author: Jack Carter

text: I absolutely cannot wait to watch this movie, but I won’t lie, I also see where many people are b****ing about, and this is going to take a while... Yes the Jaegers move a little fast for their size, I get that, yet who knows, it could’ve been accurate as f*** in that time, I mean (and only Japanese fans could get this) look at another mech series Evangelion (one that some say these jaegers are copying) and they’re fast as f*** despite being taller than the buildings around, and that takes place in freaking 2015 (I suggest looking it up to see where I’m going), plus the Kaiju still maintain that slow build so I don’t see the problem there, also for English people, Striker Eureka was also quick to move, I mean seriously Yes the battles taking in broad daylight may remove the seriousness the previous had, but just because it’s a battle to decide the fate of the planet doesn’t always be dark and brooding, though yeah, I get it makes the movie less fun, yet there’s still some dark moments this movie has And I get where people are getting with everything else, like this movie looking like transformers, Im a bit iffy about the music as well and that last scene, was there a point in putting that in? Still, I suggest refraining from calling this s*** Before actually watching it

text: Guillermo added something to the first one. Something other robot franchises failed in. The first one had a sense of reality to it. It could make you believe that it is really happening. The slow paced movement of the jaegers that gives you perspective on their weight and height. The “no hope” feel of the movie and most of all, arguably the greatest ‘sacrifice everything for victory’ monologue since independence day. This looks like a straight cgi overkill. A predictable storyline. The playboy/wildchild son of the great war hero who doesn’t think he’s good enough to fill his dad’s shoes but ultimately does. meh I think I’ll pass on this one. Bring in Guillermo and Charlie for the third one maybe I’ll watch it.

text: Lol I see a lot of comments saying that this movie lacks realism just because the jaegers are lightweight and can do backflips. The thing is, the majority of action-packed movie-goers do not expect realism in movies, especially a movie that involves giant robots and monsters. So when the producers think about this majority, it simply means more profit. If they make the movie too realistic, I believe not many people are gonna watch it, thus less profit. For the first movie, I heard many people didn't like the night battle, which is why they make the sequel with daylight battle.   Personally, I like the first one. And I know the sequel is gonna be good. Not great though. I don't mind if the jaegers manage to backflip, although I kinda agree that it defies physics. But who cares? As long as there are giant robots in action, I'm in.   Also, I think that most people who condemn this movie are actually gonna watch it, probably to condemn it more, which is kinda stupid. Lol.

text: I think that in the 1st movie Del Toro made the Jeagers' movement very real. It was delayed, slow, never failing to remind viewers that these..things we're watching are mechs that weigh hundreds of tons. In the 2 trailers released until now, I think this movie has got rid of that vibe, unfortunately. The speed with which the robots move are too smooth, too fast, reminding me of the Transformers. Not that I will stop becoming a fan of the series, however I wont be expecting too much. Also I want Hans Zimmer back too :( These soundtracks dont sound dope at all

text: It's feels like watching 5 or six variations of Striker eureka fight monsters. WHERE ARE THE UNIQUE PERSONALITIES OF THESE ROBOTS THAT WE FELL IN LOVE WITH?!? Cherno alpha was the big Russian boxing champion type. Crimson Typhoon HAD *THREE ARMS*. Striker eureka was the generic "latest and greatest" with a prideful asshole for a pilot. And Gypsy Danger felt like the old veteran that still had a few tricks up her sleeve. The only truly unique mech I saw in this trailer was the little one hat kinda rolled up into a ball. The rest feel like Striker Eureka clones. P.S. my favorite  was Cherno Alpha

text: Eh, what's with all the color & all that bright skies? This almost looks like a Power Rangers sequel. One of the thing that makes the first Pacific Rim movie so memorable is its dimly lit & grim look of the landscape; the Kaiju vs Jaeger battles happened on a stormy sea, on a rainy night in Hongkong, and underwater for the final fight. I believe this was because of GDT influence as the director & his expertise in creating spooky feeling on a monster movie.   But since John Boyega is here, im still gonna watch it at the theaters, hoping i'm wrong judging it just from the trailers & can get the same feeling of awesomeness that i got when i watch the first movie.

text: Well, where to start? I didn't really like the music, but that's just personal taste, so YMMV.   The constant trailer cuts are obnoxious, but that's not a new thing.  The slow motion stuff looks pretty stupid, I really hope they don't use it much, because that's a cliche that can just go away.   Kidvangelion? Please, no. When did this 'young adults in everything' trend start, the Hunger Games? It irks me, but if the script does it right, and the actors do a decent job, then it's fine. But that's kind of a lot of *if* there.   All the weird weapons and new controls? We'll see. Again, it depends on if it's done well, or just shat all over the film.   Now, the EXTREEEEEME Jager jumping, leaping, and sliding? Please, God, no, why? WHY are giant robots weighing tonnes in the four digit range running around like this is Tron 2?   And lastly, lets get to possibly the biggest issue: WHY on EARTH is someone from Earth trying to bring *world-destroying monsters back*?! If this isn't turning out that Newt turned traitor because of being brainwashed over time when he drifted with that brain in the first movie, it's going to be so very, *very* stupid.

text: This only cements my fears. They've taken away what made the fights awesome in the original: the weight and scale. When Jeagers moved in the original, they didn't run, jump, and flip all over the place, they had to build up to that, because they were giant mechas. The weight behind their attacks made them feel way more satisfying to watch. The scaling also helped make the both the Jeagers and Kaiju seem huge and intimidating, making everything and everyone around them seem tiny and insignificant in comparison. And I know there's people out there who make the excuse that "these are more advanced Jeagers.", yeah, but they're still giant mechas, they shouldn't be doing a lot of the stuff seen here. By removing all of this they're making it look like a Bayformers movie. The Megazord in Power Rangers had more weight and somewhat better scaling.

This is bright and colorful as hell, it seems comical almost. And the way they animate the Jaegers and Kaijus is different too. Its more fluid, more human, most importantly, its too fast. The way the first movie animated it was perfect. Jaegers were slow, hulking masses of towering metal, you could feel the weight of every step it took, every impact it made. The Kaijus were the same as well, flesh bobbed to and fro as they moved, giving the feeling that they truly are hulking masses of flesh and bone. Honestly, judging from the trailers, I might pass. I still want this movie to be successful though, maybe we can get a third one directed by Guillermo and its actually done right :/

text: A handsome man went into a hotel and asked to see the boss. When the boss came, the story began.  -The client: is room 39 empty? -The boss: yes, sir. -The client: can I book it? -The boss: of course you can. -The client: thank you.  Before going to the room, the client asked the boss to provide him with a black knife, a white thread 39 cm and an orange 73g.  The boss agreed though he was surprized at the weird things the client asked to have.  The client went into his room, he didn't ask for food or anything else.  Unfortunately for the boss, his room was next to room 39.  After midnight, the boss heard strange voices and noise in that client's room. Voices of wild animals and of utensils and dishes being thrown on the floor.  The boss didn't sleep that night. He kept thinking and wondering what might be the source of the noise.  In the morning, when the client handed the keys to the boss, the latter asked to see the room first.  He went to the room and found everything alright. Nothing unusual. He even found the thread, the black knife and the orange on the table.  The client paid the bill and gave the bellboys a very good tip and left the hotel smiling.  The boss was in a shock but he didn't reveal what he heard to the bellboys. In fact, he started to doubt himself.  After one year, the client showed up again. He asked to see the boss again. The boss was in a puzzle.  The client asked the same things: room 39, black knife, white thread 39cm and an orange 79g.  This time, the boss wanted to know the truth by all means possible. He spent a sleepless night, waiting for something to happen. After midnight, the same voices and noises started, this time louder and more indecipherable than the year before.  Again, before leaving, the client paid his bill and left a large tip on the table for the bellboys. The smile didn't leave his face.  The boss started searching for the meaning of everything the client asked to have. Why did he ask room 39? why the white thread? why the black knife??? In fact, the boss didn't arrive to any convincing answer to all these questions.  The boss now was eagerly waiting for the month of March, the month in which the client showed up.   To his surprise, on the first day of March, the same client showed up. He asked the same questions. Wanted to book the same room, wanted to have the same things as before.  The boss again heard the same noises, this time more louder than before.  In the morning, when the client was leaving the hotel, the boss apologized politely to the client and asked to know the secret behind the noises in the room.  -''If I tell you the secret, do you promise to never reveal it to anyone else?'' -''I promise I will never let anyone know''. -''Swear'' -''I swear I won't reveal your secret'' So finally, the client revealed his secret to the boss.   Unfortunately, the boss was a sincere person. Until now he hasn't revealed his secret to anyone.  When he does, I will let you know... thank you for reading.

This looks like Power Rangers, who the fuck designed those new Jaegers? And how can a kid ride a Jaeger? Like, you can't have a single emotional slip while riding one of those. And they are freaking adolescents. That's pretty stupid. Not to mention those horrible punchlines and cringe-as-fuck shots. text: Can't wait for THIS kind of thing to hit VR. As a movie...The first one was "Okay". It did nothing that we've not seen from a dozen other sources, the alien's reason for making giant monsters of all things (instead of something like say, a highly contagious plague that can jump species which really could have been done during the Dino age like it said they first tried in the movie) to wipe out the world's current denizens has been done to death (also from a dozen or more sources). But personal nitpicks aside, as long as it does at least as good as the first, it'll be "Okay" too. If it doesn't....then the monster fights will look awesome, and the rest of it will be "When will we stop looking at the people and get back to the monster-robot fights?" And be placed one after the other in roughly 15 minutes on a video here on youtube a few months later. And within a few more months, more people will have seen that Youtube video than having seen the full movie itself.

text: Part of what made the original fights so good is that the giant machines had *WEIGHT* to them. Every movement they made actually looked like it was a giant machine making it. I don't care that they've been 'upgraded', they don't move like giant robots but look like some mix of Gundam and Power Rangers. I"ll probably watch it, because I enjoyed the first one so much, but my hopes aren't high. Mind you, my expectations were pretty low for the first one, and I ended up loving that.
author: Kira

text: This looks badass. The thing I didn’t like about the first one wasn’t that the story was lackluster or anything (what fucking dickhead went into a movie about giant mechs punching giant monsters expecting a good story), it was that there wasn’t enough action in it, and the lead guy wasn’t charismatic enough to make the bridges to the action fun enough. The movie had stretches where the action was abscent in favor of these stories that honestly came second to the main pull of these films, making me feel like a 10 year old again. Hopefully this time the film is more dense with that sweet sweet action, and that Boyega will liven it all up. If anyone is actually taking this shit seriously, they need to get a reality check. Transformers left too much of a shitty taste in my mouth last year when it came to giant robot action, I’m just hoping this one cleanses my pallet.

Take it for what it is and enjoy the 'holy shit'.  Not all great movies follow the same formula.

text: I have some concerns  1. The movements of the jaegers- They just look too fast. I've been reading the comments and seeing people complain about the movements being to fast and people defending it saying "Its set further in the future so of course they'd be faster". The complaint about movement speed is stemming from the fact that because of how slow the movements were in the first movie it gave a feeling of weight and power to the jaegers, combined with the sounds it really felt like a 300 ton punching machine. Along with that I'd describe the fighting style of each movie as a heavy weight boxing/wrestling match for the first movie and ninja like fighting for uprising. I'm not entirely opposed to the fast movement decision if it was limited to 1/3 to 1/2 the jaegers, not most if not all judging by the trailer.  2.The jaeger design- This isn't as big of a problem but I'm not optimistic about most of the designs. Most of the jaegers seem to be going for the striker/typhoon slim design(though I'd say S/T did it better). It just seems to take away from the power of the jaegers making them seem like less of a giant machine and more(as people in the comments have already pointed out) seem more like transformers or power rangers. I do however like the look of(forgive me for not knowing his actual name) mace fist.  3. The characters- With the exception of John Boyegas character, the new characters look like they're going to be susceptible to the media trend of adding strong young/minority/female characters only to completely miss the mark and make them feel forced, lazily written and instead of being a strong character coming off as bitchy and unlikable(take Sarah Palmer from halo 4-5 as an example).   I love the first movie and yes, i know this is just a trailer and I'm desperately hoping its good, but the fact that its not being directed by Guillermo Del Toro is the main thing giving me concerns about this movie. The man knew what made his movie great and without his mind behind this, it is very hard to put faith in this sequel.

text: Sad how the 'hip' thing is 'OMG it's not Directed by Del Toro it's just Transformers'....it is almost like nobody actually saw the first film. It was absolutely a cut above the average Transformers-type of blockbuster, but it was far from some flawless masterpiece.  The character archetypes used in the film were very pure and simple, they were all drawn in pretty one-note fashion. They've talked about how they are going for more complexity in the characters in this film.  Charlie Hunnam lacks charisma as a lead, ask the King Arthur movie. John Boyega has a lot more on-screen charisma.  The first film had pacing issues, and a middle chunk(Before the battle of Hong Kong) that takes too long to get going. It needed to be leaned out in the editing room. The Director is shooting for 2 hours with this film.  The first film shrouded all of its action scenes in rain, water, and night time. Interesting aesthetic choice, but fight scenes in broad daylight allow the fan to appreciate them in all of their glory.  The Director has stated his influences included Ultraman and Godzilla, which were among influences for Del Toro. They built off the Story Bible Del Toro developed on the first film. The notion of a Kaiju-Jaeger Hybrid? The concept of someone betraying humanity? Those are both ideas that Del Toro mentioned back in the early development of the sequel.  This movie is cut from the same cloth as the first film and honestly feels like a natural extension and evolution of that world. Only we're going to get a more charismatic lead, more interesting characters, and a better paced film. It's going to surprise everyone by being an improvement over the first film.

text: The first one was good because it was over the top, didn't take itself seriously and had the feel of a classic cheesy monster movie. That was what made it fantastic.  Now we've got a movie that looks like it's going to take itself seriously and have none of Guillermo's passion or quirkiness.   And I still don't buy that Stacker had a son we never heard of. I hate it when they do that shit. Not once did he ever mention having a son (even when Herc was talking about how Stacker was taking 'his son'). He didn't say "I know. I have a son too." It was always implied that Mako was his only family, even if she was 'adopted'. Mako also never mentions having a brother/adopted brother.  So that's going to be cringy in and of itself.

text: I loved the first one and the tone of this seems so different. It's just a trailer so maybe the final product will be different but it felt like robots were moving too fast and were to agile which were always one of the issues I had with the transformers movies. One of the things I loved about the first movie was that it felt like the Jaegers and Kaiju had real weight behind them. They were big massive tanks, not robot ninjas jumping around.   Another thing is how bright everything is shot here, it felt more epic with all the major fights being at night since it made the colors of the cities, the Jaegers and the Kaijus being sliced and hit really stand out. Set the clips in the trailer at night and they would look way more epic.   And of course the music choice for this was fucking awful. The trailer for the original had this awesome dark rock guitar that fit the theme perfectly, this is just generic Hip Hop.   If this is survival, as the trailer says, then I don't think I want them to survive.

text: Alright I noticed that people are thinking Transformers when they see this. Let me explain.  The Purpose of the Pan Pacific Defense Core was not only defeat Kaiju threats but also use as a way to share their technology with other countries in creating better Jagers without leaking top secret schematics. The Mark V Striker Eureka was the fastest one ever built, and it was essential to make faster Jagers since Catagory 4 Kaiju were smarter. In order to do so the builders found ways to make them slimmer and taller along with recreating the Drift System to help with reaction time.  For reference I look through the Universal Century of Gundam. That spanned Through 14 years where the Earth Federation and Zeon kept sending more Advanced Machines to battle another just as Advanced Machines. Pacific Rim Still is more relatable to Japanese Mecha Anime than Transformers.

text: Onslaught 1 second ago I'll leave this here as an explanation on how the jaegers do backflips.  The Mark-6 Jaegers were built during the ten-year period following the Kaiju War. While some believed the Kaiju were no longer a threat, others chose to be cautious and were motivated to resume construction of the Jaegers. The Mark-6 Jaegers reportedly represent "the pinnacle of human invention". Mark-6 Jaeger's use "state-of-the-art" hologram technology, and stand at 250' tall.  Mark-6 Jaegers were designed with "sleeker frames" and use "high octane burst replusors". Speed and velocity were increased, and the armor plating of the Jaegers utilized newer, lightweight reinforced steel armor material. The fighting strength of Mark-6 Jaegers utilize over 30,000 pounds of force, allowing them to move in ways that were not possible for their predecessors.

I understand that everyone is getting angry over the fact that the Jaegers are faster and sleeker in this version, but it actually kind of makes sense.   Uprising takes place, in Del Toro's words when he was still working on the project, "A few years after the first one". A few years could range from anywhere from 5 years to 15 years. Let's say it takes place 5 years ahead of the first one just in case. This amount of time allows for multitudes of upgrades to be made to the Jaeger design, and of course, the countries would continue to make them (because they would either be 1. Skeptical of a secondary alien invasion or 2. Skeptical of other countries abusing this mechanical power as a militaristic strength). When so many engineers and scientists are focussing on one thing at any given time, a LOT usually gets done. This means that the research and development could have skyrocketed without the impending Kaiju invasion. This explains why the Jaegers could be so sleek and faster.   I know everyone's getting pissed off about it, but I mean we're all really here to see massive robots v kaiju action here, so I still have hope for it (even if it's just a little bit).

text: The movie looks good, i can clearly see the difference in direction though. Both directors and the franchise in general are inspired in mecha anime like Gundam and evangelion. But Del Toro has always had a proclivity to make fantastic things as realistic looking as possible. Like when using so many real puppets in pan's laberynth or Hellboy 2, or when making the jaegers so slow in the first one so you could feel their weight. This new director on the other hand is going all out anime. Making these mechs do crazy stunts. Neither of these styles is right or wrong, they are just different.

text: Majority of Star Wars Films’ Writers & Directors Are White Men  07 Feb, 2018  A new report reveals that in 41 years of the Star Wars franchise, 96 percent of writers and directors hired by Lucasfilm for the movies are white men. George Lucas introduced the world to a galaxy far, far away in 1977 with Star Wars: A New Hope, a space opera he wrote and directed. The stories of Luke Skywalker (Mark Hamill), Leia Organa (Carrie Fisher), and Han Solo (Harrison Ford) captured the attention of moviegoers around the world and inspired a legion of dedicated fans spanning multiple generations. Though it seemed the franchise had concluded with the final installment of Lucas’ prequel trilogy, Disney acquired Lucasfilm in 2012 and announced a revival of the Star Wars film series.  The episodic storyline was relaunched with J.J. Abrams’ Star Wars: The Force Awakens in 2015, but Disney and Lucasfilm also put standalone anthology movies into development, the first of which was Gareth Edwards’ Rogue One: A Star Wars Story in 2016. Rian Johnson’s Star Wars: The Last Jedi is the latest entry of the franchise to hit theaters, but there are plenty more coming, including Ron Howard’s Solo: A Star Wars Story, Johnson’s new trilogy, and the recently announced series of films from Game of Thrones creators David Benioff and D.B. Weiss. However, as Lucasfilm puts more and more movies into development, fans have wondered when the studio will hire a man of color, woman of color, or white woman to helm or direct a Star Wars movie.  Variety’s Maureen Ryan crunched the numbers in terms of gender and racial representation in major creative roles on the past and confirmed upcoming Star Wars movies. For 17 total films – including the original, prequel, and current trilogies, confirmed anthologies, Johnson’s trilogy, and the new series from Benioff and Weiss (which Ryan estimates will include three films, though Lucasfilm did not announce the exact number of movies they’ll produce) – Lucasfilm hired a total of 24 people in roles as writers or directors. Of those 24 people, all but one were white men; the exception is Leigh Brackett, who received a screenplay credit on 1980’s The Empire Strikes Back. Ryan summed up her findings: “Otherwise, no men of color, women of color or white women have held these positions. The franchise’s leading creative voices have been white men 96% of the time.”   For her findings, writers included anyone who received a screenplay or story credit on a Star Wars film. Ryan also included writers and directors who were fired from or left confirmed Star Wars projects, including Star Wars IX’s Colin Trevorrow as well as Solo’s Phil Lord and Chris Miller. However, Josh Trank, who was attached to direct a Star Wars standalone film before departing after the failure of his Fantastic Four, is not included in Ryan’s breakdown (though, if he were included, the percent calculated by Ryan wouldn’t change). The breakdown also only includes feature films, and doesn’t include those who have worked on Star Wars TV series like Star Wars: The Clone Wars and Star Wars Rebels.  To be clear, this breakdown of representation only looks at those who are writing and directing Star Wars movies; Ryan made note that the Star Wars movies released since 2012 have made strides in terms of more diverse casts and characters. However, movie writers and directors are undoubtedly the most important roles in terms of shaping and bringing these stories to life. And the call for more diversity in these creative roles extends beyond the galaxy far, far away.  With the likes of Patty Jenkins’ Wonder Woman and Jordan Peele’s Get Out finding critical and financial success, and hype surrounding Ryan Coogler’s Black Panther and Ava DuVernay’s A Wrinkle in Time, movie fans have made it clear they’re interested in stories told from other perspectives. While it’s possible Lucasfilm may hire men of color, women of color, and white women for their upcoming films – including those from Johnson, Benioff and Weiss – many fans are frustrated by the current lack of diversity in major creative roles on the Star Wars franchise. And looking at the numbers presented by Ryan, it’s clear to see why.  KEY RELEASE DATES Solo: A Star Wars Story release date: May 25, 2018 Star Wars 9 / Star Wars: Episode IX release date: Dec 20, 2019... now it's racial... how dumb can that be... next thing you know they'll be hitting Godzilla for not being Russian made...

text: While I did think the chunky movements of the Jaegers in the original looked awesome, I don't really think this is that unrealistic to think about. After all, during the Kaiju War, they were under pressure to constantly develop better Jaegers. And we all know how well most people work under pressure. The movie was released in 2013, so it can only be assumed that the first Kaiju attacks happened in 2013. 14 months later, in 2015, they deployed the first Mark-1 Jaeger. TWO YEARS LATER, in July 2017, they deployed the Gypsy Danger, a Mark-3, which is shown to be notably more agile than the Cherno Alpha (Mark-1). And in 2019, they launched the Mark-5 Jaegers (of which we only know about Striker Eureka), which was a lot more agile than Gypsy Danger was, both before and after the Mark-3 Reactivation Program. Considering how much the technology advanced under pressure, where nobody had the time to sit down, relax and think things through properly, I'm not really surprised that the Jaegers in Uprising are in a whole different league than the ones in the original. And besides, they've had several years to develop new Jaegers, in case the Kaiju were to return, and it's not unrealistic to assume that the different countries would constantly try to do something better than the rest. I'm not sure I understand why there's a need for a Jaeger with a Morph Ball mode though, but I suppose there's only one way to find out. And that is by watching the sequel when it comes out.  And yes, I literally just re-watched the first movie. For the third time. I freaking LOVE that movie! I'm going to watch Uprising when it comes out, and I'm probably going to enjoy it like a child, since I'm a huge fan of the Mecha-genre.    Also, it's never been stated that the Jaegers are supposed to be Real Robot-type Mecha...

text: To those here who are saying "Oh my god this is just transformers but bigger, it's gonna be shit" or "looks like power rangers and shit. Gonna be a terrible movie", stop and think for a moment. Lore wise, it makes perfect sense that the jeagers would evolve to become much more agile and maneuverable. Most of the jeagers in the first movie aside from Gipsy after being repaired and Striker were clunky and slow. Jeagers were destroyed because most of the time, the kaiju were much faster (i.e. Otachi blitzing Gipsy and Crimson).  Now look at this from an inspiration point of view. I can guarantee that these jeagers are inspired by Evas, Gundams, and Jet Jagur from Godzilla. This and the first one arent movies made to be some adaptation of an American cartoon. Pacific rim is supposed to be an American interpretation of the kaiju/mecha anime genre. Just look at how the jeagers move. They aren't moving like humans like a transformer and it's not cheesy and glamorized like a megazord. It's fluid but still robot like. You can tell they are being controlled and that they are still machines.   Bottom line, comparisons with transformers and shit shouldn't be made because they are nothing alike

text: I've seen the first one which was having a more serious tone. The initial tragedy of Raleigh losing his brother set a tone to the movie which just captured me instantly and made it so much more intimate. This sequel is not made out of the mould of the first one which is not a bad thing. But the first movie just seemed so real, the music was spot on and inspiring. It wasn't trying to be anything but just a good story. The focus wasn't on just the Jaegers and their pilots, but on many little things which all added to the flavor. Pacific Rim 2 just feels like a short episode of some robot action cartoon series which will have a lot of fighting and bad teen drama. But I maybe wrong.

text: You have a director that has never done a big budget movie before (and a writer for the Transformers cinematic universe) and John Boyega (first time producer) stupidly wanting faster jagers. At the end of Pacific Rim the Kaiju were already moving pretty fast and the Jagers were keeping up. How fast would these new Kaiju be now to merit stupidly faster Jagers? It breaks the immersion of a giant fight. Just take out all the buildings and all you see are robots fighting aliens not some grand battle against giant beasts.   And you also have the studio thing of let's have pre teen pilots to appeal to kids. And let's have more of everything (Jagers and Kaiju) so we can milk the toy market. That is literally what Transformers is and this is what Pacific Rim has become of it and you can see it in the trailers. If you can't see that the you are in denial and I hope you have some humility and admit when you see how shit this in the theater.

text: Why are they suddenly children pilots? or atleast very young individuals, the first film it felt like it was a godzilla type of thing, bleak, horrible existance, death and destruction where only godzilla could save humanity, much like the first film where mistakes could not happen because people die, ripped apart, killed off, severe consequences ... this one feels like its going to be a power rangers remake, all colourful, made for kids you know what i mean? like "with the power of love, we can defeat them!" *facepalm  you know what i mean though? its like i went from watching something dark and sinister, to watching yet another transformers film, even the jaegers, they moved rather realistically like they had real weight to them, now they are jumping around and being tossed about like physics suddenly no longer applies to them - i bet you no kids die in this film, i bet they all survive and they all live happily ever after.  Theres nothing wrong with that, it just makes the film feel like im no longer watching pacific rim, the darkness and sinister approach, looks lost ... power rangers feat transformers, kids will love it but i personally am no longer interested if thats their aim.  Another comparison is Marvel and DC, DC is the first film, Marvel took over for the second, again, im not saying thats bad, just that i would have preferred it if DC also did the second :/ lol

text: This is what happens when a novice director and a bunch of TV writers trying to make a sequel without actually understanding what makes the first movie so great. They’re like kids given opportunity to play with an excellent original material but fall short when they thought that people want to see big robots fighting monsters and leveling cities, with shiny CGI and loud sounds is the main theme. Del Toro’s version is a human theme story, with Raleigh Beckett losing his brother and try to live with the memory, Pentecost’s protective father instinct on a little girl he help raised as his own, the strain father and son relationship between Chuck and Herc Hansen, Mako’s struggle to get revenge for her families death and desire to prove her self to Pentecost. All this are human emotions and story with robots vs monsters as backdrop. It’s how Del Toro can make a movie of a woman having sex with a fish man, an appealing award winning movie.

I never again watch and read comments and trailers anymore. I loved the movie, it exactly got what I loved. The action, stunts, plot twists and to be honest, I kinda like this sequel. Also, I didnt find any annoying character here as in some movies there are. The blue light and feel of the base where Jags were was cool! What is more, I thought that I would really be upset to see super kids saving the day, but to be honest, the Amara was not annoying kid, she was genuinely likeable character. I liked the characters even though they didnt have enough developement, maybe Im shallow. I really wish this would got a good box office and we would see trilogy. Please, dont get distracted by bad comments here. If you liked the first you will like this too. Also, about the fast moving Jaegers, they felt heavy and big. I loved that they were more agile. Not all Jaegers were doing the flips. At last, do you know why I loved Pacific Rim? I have never seen anyone say this but, the thought of humans joining together, and creating bigger robot, which have looks like us, which just reflect our creativity, logic, nature and physic understanding. That our physic weakness goes away. Im not sure if I said this good but here are mine words. Thanks for reading and have a great day!

Maybe the first Pacific Rim was ridiculous and over the top, but everything about it was so much fun, exhilarating and a visual masterpiece, while this one is plain and simple painfull to watch. I only  liked Scrapy's run in the begining. It all went to hell after that.

But this one is almost a joke(sometimes cringeworthy and corny), its a mixture of teeny cast, bad acting, and not so great story. I couldn't take this movie serious. The casting of the first one was perfect, the story and action was great. With that said i guess this second movie is not horrible though, that is thanks to the robot fighting action...5/10 for movie.

text: Ruined this movie. They took what made the first one gritty and real, and turned it into a attempt to make a high box office blockbuster for children. People liked the first one because they seemed like massive machines ran by engines. These are just like transformers that are organic. Pacific rim was one of my favorites, and this is not that. It's a clear attempt to make a franchise, but really ultimately will kill itself off by following transformers down the toilet. It is like power Rangers are piloting tranformers. It's actually really dissapointing. If this had been the first movie, it would never have spawn a second. And they only reason people will want a third, is to hope it's like the first and you trash the teeny bopping and go back to grown people filmaking.

text: I watched the movie. I thought it sucked. The movie ended with me not caring about any of the characters or even remembering their names. There is zero balance between storytelling and action scenes, and storytelling is almost absent in this movie. There were several references to the black guy in the first film, probably because people would not remember who the new black guy is unless they referenced him every other scene. Only thing I thought was decent in this film, was the cgi.  Also, most of the cast are teenagers, with the senior officers being in their early to mid 20s. You'll enjoy this if you are barely into your teens or have the intelligence, sense of humor, and maturity of your typical 10-13 year old.  The movie is bad in my opinion. First Pacific Rim is decent.

text: IDK what people are talking about, this part is fine as solid shit (to me).  No hate, I love Raleigh Becket, I really hoped I could see him again in this sequel, but he was really predictable as a protagonist, everyone knew that he suffered trauma, that he would overcome it, that he would eventually win the Kaiju, somehow. He was somewhat a douche, he got into fights and shit but then an Asian woman would appear and slap him in the face for him to be righteous, we all saw that coming. But here, we got a black main protagonist who just doesn't give a single shit all the time even after his sister died, people don't know what the fuck he's gonna do, he just walks around like "Yeah you can hate me to the bone but that's your problem idc lmao", but later into the movie it shows that he actually cares, he actually knows his way around, and is a total badass. I seriously thought he was supposed to be the Commander since that Chinese Commander had death flags all over his head, and Nake along with Namani will do the job as Pilots. That's what makes this part stand out for me. An interesting main character. Same with the story, first we gotta admit both are shit, but this part got a really nice plot that the first one doesn't. I didn't saw that. One more plus point.  As for the visual, are people blind? As for the music, are people deaf? I know, I know the thing called "opinion" but I'm arguing so *change my mind* !

text: This movie was very..... Alright. A lot of people were complaining about the jaegers feeling weightless and too fast but that wasn't a problem. This takes place years after the first movie and the technology was much more advanced, making them way faster. That being said the jaeger vs kaiju scenes were pretty great and the jaeger vs jaeger parts were almost perfect. The story itself was pretty solid thanks to Del Torro and for the most part the action was awesome. The designs for the monsters and jaegers I think were more original in the first movie. My biggest issue was with the kids they put in main roles. I didn't like a single one and at times it was downright annoying watching them and the sript was absolute garbage. They just took away from the seriousness of many scenes. Fin and discount Paul Walker did alright but I would prefer more of the original cast to return in the third movie if it happens. Id still go see it. I really hope Del Torro is in the directors seat.
